{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17566248","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17566248"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:37:26+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:37:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18733"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18733","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18733"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.04,0.52,0.03,0.31]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11465"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104100"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11465","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11465"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18733"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86419"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"26"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"489"},{"type":"tags","id":"4487"},{"type":"tags","id":"9222"},{"type":"tags","id":"12912"},{"type":"tags","id":"12921"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26539"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37324"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37337"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104100","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/104100"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman is admitted to the Intensive Care Unit with septic shock secondary to pneumonia. She has a history of breast cancer diagnosed six months ago and is immunosuppressed on chemotherapy. A right subclavian central venous catheter was inserted one week ago for administration of vasopressors and antibiotics. She now has a three-day history of progressive right arm swelling and pain. She has no chest pain or shortness of breath. Her medical history includes hypertension in addition to the breast cancer. Her medications include amlodipine and chemotherapy agents.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell but is improving. Her pulse rate is 95/min, blood pressure 110/70 mmHg on reducing doses of noradrenaline, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 96% on 2L/min nasal cannula oxygen, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. Her right arm is swollen and tender compared to the left, with prominent superficial veins. The central line insertion site appears clean with no erythema or discharge. The catheter flushes and aspirates normally.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Superior vena cava syndrome","Catheter-related infection","Venous thrombosis","Cellulitis","Lymphatic obstruction"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with unilateral arm swelling and pain one week after central venous catheter insertion. The presence of active cancer, chemotherapy, and critical illness creates multiple risk factors for thrombosis. Central venous catheter-related thrombosis is a common complication, occurring in up to 50% of patients with central lines, and the risk is particularly high in patients with malignancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVenous thrombosis\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with unilateral extremity swelling, pain, and prominent superficial veins due to venous congestion. The presence of a central line, active cancer, and critical illness are significant risk factors. Diagnosis is typically confirmed with ultrasound, and treatment involves anticoagulation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECellulitis\u003C/strong\u003E would typically present with erythema, warmth, and tenderness of the affected area. While it can cause swelling, the absence of skin changes or signs of infection at the catheter site makes this diagnosis less likely, even in an immunocompromised patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELymphatic obstruction\u003C/strong\u003E can cause arm swelling and would be a consideration given her history of breast cancer with axillary involvement. However, the acute onset and presence of pain make venous thrombosis more likely as the primary diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESuperior vena cava syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with facial and bilateral upper extremity swelling, along with other symptoms such as dyspnoea and facial plethora, which are not present in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECatheter-related infection\u003C/strong\u003E would typically present with fever, erythema or discharge at the insertion site, or worsening signs of infection. Despite her immunocompromised state, the improving clinical condition and clean appearance of the insertion site make this diagnosis less likely.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Central venous catheter-related thrombosis occurs in up to 50% of patients and presents with unilateral arm swelling and pain.","Cancer and immunosuppression significantly increase the risk of catheter-related thrombosis.","Ultrasound is the first-line imaging modality for suspected central venous catheter-related thrombosis."],"references":["Brown AFT, Cadogan MD, Celenza A, Ruedy J, Marshall SA. Marshall \u0026 Ruedy\u2019s On Call: Principles \u0026 Protocol. Elsevier Australia; 2017. Available at: https://www.elsevierhealth.com.au/marshall-ruedys-on-call-9780729542452.html","Kornbau C, Lee KC, Hughes GD, Firstenberg MS. Central line complications. Int J Crit Illn Inj Sci. 2015 Jul-Sep;5(3):170\u2013178. doi: 10.4103/2229-5151.164940. Available at: https://doi.org/10.4103/2229-5151.164940"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86419"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18733"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86419","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/86419"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-29T12:44:49+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-29T12:45:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11465"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104100"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"26","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/26"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd7c","name":"Critical Care Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"